 Adoption of New Technologies in Ethiopian 
 Farming: 
 The Case of Tegulet-Bulga District, 
 Shoa Area of control/area of land 
 Yohannes Kebede, Kisan Gunjal and Garth Coffin 
 Department of Farming-based Money flow, McGill University, Ste. Anne de Bellevue, Que., H9X 1CO 
 (Canada) 
 
 (Accepted 31 March 1989) 
 
 Abstract 
 Kebede, Y., Gunjal, K. and Coffin, G., 1990. Adoption of new technologies in Ethiopian farming: the case ofTegulet-Bulga District, Shoa Area of control/area of land. Agric. Econ., 4: 27-43. 
 Adoption of farming-based production technologies in developing countries is influenced by a wide 
 range of money-based and social factors as well as physical and technical parts of farming and the 
 risk (point of view/way of behaving) of farmers. It is important to understand the role of these factors to secure/make sure of the 
 development of appropriate technologies and the design of successful development projects. This 
 study examines the hit/effect of such factors on the adoption of single-ox, (material that makes plants grow better) and bug-killer 
 technologies as part of a after-drought recovery project in Tegulet-Bulga district in Ethiopia. 
 Models to test the chance of adoption are specified for the (pertaining to each person or thing) technologies and 
 are guessed using a logit maximum chance procedure. results point to/show that the most significant (number or thing that changes) affecting the chance of adoption of all three technologies is farm size; the hit/effect 
 is negative for single-ox technology and positive for (material that makes plants grow better) and bug-killer use. Money-based factors 
 such as income, wealth and (money owed)  generally show (meaningful numbers) influence on the adoption of single-ox and bug-killer technologies as do family size, access to outside information, education and experience. 
 The effect of (related to how much money and power people have) factors on adoption of (material that makes plants grow better) and bug-killer technologies is greater 
 in the area which has more access to outside information and off-farm activities (Ankober) than 
 in more 'self-contained' area (Seladengay). The hit/effect of the degree of risk disgust of farmers 
 is found to be significant and negative for single-ox technology in both areas, and for (material that makes plants grow better) and 
 bug-killer technologies in only one area. The (described the future) chances of technology adoption by an 
 average farmer are found to increase very much with the level of education and access or exposure to outside information. 
 
 Introduction 
 Food production problems of African countries, especially of Ethiopia, have 
 been widely (known to many people) over the last few years. Although much attention has been fo0169-5150/90/$03.50 
 
 Â© 1990 Elsevier Science Publishers B.V. 
 
 28 
 
 cused on emergency relief, the important element of after-drought recovery, 
 and the long-term food supply, is the provision and adoption of appropriate 
 production technologies. 
 Development programs in Ethiopia over the past twenty years, have included 
 a few new technologies. Among the latestly introduced are single-ox, 
 bug-killers and (material that makes plants grow better) usage. However, there has not been a wide-spread provision and adoption of these technologies in the central highlands of Ethiopia. 
 Different (related to how much money and power people have) factors and the degree of risk disgust may be the causes 
 oflow adoption rates (Teele, 1975; Jamison and Lau, 1982; O'Mara, 1983; Roe, 
 1983; Shakya and Flinn, 1985). 
 The main goal of this paper, therefore, is to (show or prove) how the different money-based, social, and physical (numbers that change/things that change) and degree of risk disgust affect 
 the adoption of three selected technologies in Ethiopian farming. Also, this study will also focus on how (one after the other) (recursive) decisions are 
 used. 
 Study places/locations 
 
 The study places/locations of Ankober and Seladengay sub-districts of Tegulet-Bulga 
 district of Shoa (related to managing and running a company or organization) area are in central Ethiopian highlands. Because of (related to where mountains, rivers, cities, etc., are located) (blocking things) (lack of roads and other means of communication) the study areas had never been accessed by any development project until1984. The main (features/ qualities/ traits) of the farmers in these areas are given 
 in Table 1. Seladengay area has a longer tradition of farming with (a) little 
