 These areas were among the areas affected by the major drought of 1984/ 
 85. The farmers were helped by a recovery project financed by Oxfam America, Oxfam UK, Medios of Belgium, CFAF of France and other donor (services businesses/government units). 
 Technical help was given by the International Animals Center for 
 Africa (ILCA). Data were collected the year following the drought when crop 
 production was (compared to other things) good. 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) of the technologies: single-ox, (material that makes plants grow better)s and 
 bug-killers 
 
 Usually/(in the past), Ethiopian farmers have used a pair of oxen for traction. However, studies of the Ethiopian highland reclamation have found that most 
 farmers do not groups of armed men  a pair of oxen (Police officer, 1983). The fast increase in 
 population has increased competition for plantable land and has resulted in (lowering in number/getting worse) grazing areas and animal population (Ministry of Farming, 1982). 
 At the same time, raising a large number of animals on limited land has exposed both plantable and non -plantable lands to soil wearing away. 
 To overcome the problem of a shortage of oxen, Ethiopian farmers have been 
 using traditional useful thing/valuable supply-exchange arrangements (McCann, 1986). The 
 practice of exchanging grain for oxen became expensive for many small 
 farmers after the drought. In order to reduce soil wearing away and avoid farm (state of owing money) from traditional exchange arrangements, ILCA developed a changed form of traction put into use to be pulled by a single-ox rather than the 
 ordinarily used pair ( Gryseels et al., 1984). So, single-ox technology 
 was one aspect of the after-drought recovery project. 
 The second technology gave/given to farmers is bug-killers. Insects such as 
 grasshoppers and American ball worms present/cause a serious problem in both study 
 places/locations. Therefore, under this project, farmers were given a small amount 
 of bug-killers at a (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) market price on an interest-free loan to be repaid in 
 3 years. 
 The third production technology thought about/believed is the provision of (not living) 
 (material that makes plants grow better)s. In order to reduce the loss of life-creating ability of their farm lands, some 
 farmers have tried to use farm yard poop/fertilizer (FYM). But the FYM practice 
 needs/demands more animals to produce enough poop/fertilizer. It also needs/demands more labour 
 than that gave by 4 to 5 family members to distribute the poop/fertilizer on the 
 field. Therefore, the practice is mostly restricted to gardens. Where (not living) 
 (material that makes plants grow better) has been used produces /gives up are generally much higher. (not living) (material that makes plants grow better) is 
 gave/given through the Ministry of Farming at a price set by the government. 
 Not all farmers used or meant to use the above three production technologies. The thrust of this study is, therefore, to identify the factors that moti- 
 
 30 
 
 vated farmers to use or not to use single-ox, bug-killers and (material that makes plants grow better), and the 
 extent to which these factors were important in farmers' decisions. 
 
 Models of adoption behaviour 
 Some studies have (examined closely) the influence of different (related to how much money and power people have) factors on the desire of decision makers to use new technologies 
 (Nerlove and Press, 1973; Roe, 1983; Shakya and Flinn, 1985). In most studies 
 of adoption behaviour the (thing that changes (like a test score) because of something else that you control (like study time)) is held back to lie between 0 
 and 1 and the models used are huge functions. Univariate and multivariate logit and probit models and their changed forms have been used a lot to study the adoption behaviour offarmers and people (Nerlove and 
 Press, 1973; Schmidt and Strauss, 1975; Garcia et al., 1983; Shakya and Flinn, 
 1985). 
 Maddala ( 1983) and Shakya and Flinn ( 1985) have recommended probit 
 models for functional forms with limited (things that change (like test scores) because of other things that you control (like study times)) that are continuous between 0 and 1, and logit models for separate (things that change (like test scores) because of other things that you control (like study times)). In this 
 study the responses recorded are separate ((to both people or groups equally) exclusive and thorough) 
 and therefore a univariate logit model will be developed. 
 For analysis of the adoption of technology packages, some studies have proposed (happening together) decision models (Feder et al., 1985). Watched/followed behaviour 
 in some areas, however, has showed that there is a recursive decision-making 
 process where those inputs thought about/believed very important to farm survival are adopted 
 first, followed by inputs which are believed to increase yield. For instance, the 
 plan/purpose to use (material that makes plants grow better) depends on the decision made (related to/looking at/thinking about) how to prevent crop losses from insects and sicknesses if the last thing just mentioned is a priority problem. 
 In making decisions about the adoption of a given technology, farmers are 
 assumed to weigh the results of adoption of an invention of new things against its 
 money-based, social, and technical (ability to be done). If we assume that social values or 
 technical (challenging things accomplished or completed) are a reflection of the level of money-based (challenging things accomplished or completed), 
 then a farmer tests the new technology in terms of its (in small steps up) benefit. 
 Naturally, if the money-based benefit from a technology is higher, the preference 
 or utility ( U) for that technology (assuming a monotonic relationship between 
 benefits and utility) will be higher. 
 Suppose an individual household's preference (utility) of adopting a new 
 technology, for a given vector of money-based, social and physical factors (X) is 
 represented by UN(X) and the preference (utility) of adopting the usual 
 technology by UT (X). Then, the preference for adopting the new and old technologies can be defined as a linear relationship: 
 UN(X)=XBN+EN 
 
