 The final decision of farmers is a reflection of different factors including their 
 
 32 
 
 risk preference and (related to how much money and power people have) (surrounding conditions). The risk preference of a decision maker is, itself, a function of money-based and social factors. Some studies 
 have included risk preference along with other factors in adoption models (Roe, 
 1983). If both sets of (numbers that change/things that change) are included in the models of adoption studies, 
 however, there will be high degree multicollinearity. In this study, therefore, 
 some of the (related to how much money and power people have) (numbers that change/things that change) are thrown out in order to reduce the problem of multicollinearity (Moock, 1981) and avoid problems of lack of coming together (Harrel, 1985 ). 
