 Sample 
 For the technology adoption model, a sample of 100 farmers from Ankober 
 and 80 farmers from Seladengay was randomly chosen. However, due to time, 
 money and personnel restrictions the (pertaining to each person or thing) sample size for adoption models 
 involving the risk disgust coefficient were limited to 25 and 22. Farmers who 
 had used the technology and/ or who had planned to use it next season were 
 labeled as adopters ( PA = 1) and those who were not willing to use it as 
 non -adopters (PA = 0). Farmers did not use the technologies during the period 
 of this study but who were planning to use them the next season were asked to 
 guess the benefits and identify restrictions from using these technologies. 
 This was good through the farmers own expectations, based on the 
 hit/effect of these technologies on the field of others. Finally, any over- or underestimation of benefits from using these technologies especially from farmers 
 who were planning to use them the following season were corrected on the basis 
 of a second and third-round interviews. 
 Scientific results 
 Assuming a (usually/ in a common and regular way) distributed error term (E) in equation (3a), the logit 
 maximum chance (LML) guess procedure was used to get consistent, (producing a lot with very little waste) and asymptotically (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) estimators (Amemiya, 1981; Maddala, 1983; Rahm and Huffman, 1984; Capps and Kramer, 1985). The guesses are summarized in Table 2 for Ankober and Seladengay areas and the 
 results are discussed below. 
