 of after-tax farm income on PT and off-farm income on ST were significant 
 only for Ankober. It is also obvious that the money-based benefit (measured by 
 the size of the coefficient of farm income) of single-ox and (material that makes plants grow better) technologies has a much larger hit/effect in Seladengay than in Ankober. 
 The more wealth a farmer has, the more likely he is to adopt a new technology. More wealth also hints the ability to buy another ox or availability of 
 cow(s) to be used for draft purposes, because of this (using/putting into action) a negative influence on 
 adoption of ST. The effect of wealth is found to be positive but nonsignificant 
 on adoption of bug-killers. The negative effect of wealth on adoption of ST in 
 Ankober is as expected. The positive and significant effect ofwealth on adoption of ST as watched/followed in Seladengay needs/demands added/more explanation. The practice of using a cow with an ox for traction is more common in Seladengay than 
 in Ankober. So, the more animals (hence cows) families have the more 
 willing they may be to use a single-ox. 
 The larger the (money owed)  a farmer has to pay ( X 4 ), the less willing he is to use new 
 technologies from which the benefit is uncertain. However, owing a lot 
 farmers may be willing to try ST and save on oxen useful thing/valuable supply more than the less 
 (owing money or favors) farmers. 
 The (money owed)  level has the expected effect of stopping ability to adopt as seen 
 from its negative effect on adoption of PT and F T in both areas. (in almost the same way), as 
 expected, its effect on adoption of ST is positive. The significant effect of 
 (money owed)  on adoption of F T for Seladengay might suggest that farmers in this area 
 are more risk disliking than the farmers in Ankober. 
 As farm size (X5 ) increases farmers need more traction power. If a farmer 
 judges the traction power given by a single-ox to be not enough to complete 
 critical field operations on time, then the larger the farm size, the lower is the 
 chance of adopting ST. Generally, an increase in farm size is likely to increase the chance of adoption of PT and FT (see reviews by Feder et al., 
 1985). 
 As seen from Table 2, farm size has a negative effect on adoption of ST and 
 a positive effect on adoption of PT and F T as expected. This (number or thing that changes) has the 
 most significant effect on adoption of all production technologies except on 
 the ST for Seladengay. The negative but non-significant effect of farm size on 
 adoption of ST for Seladengay may be because of limited range for expanding 
 farm size compared to Ankober. 
 With the use of bug-killers, if a farmer can prevent crop loss and get a 
 good harvest, then he may want to increase his farm income by using (material that makes plants grow better). 
 Therefore, the decision to use bug-killers can have a positive effect on the decision to use (material that makes plants grow better). 
 As expected, the argument of the (when two things work together equally well) between bug-killers and 
 (material that makes plants grow better) and the recursive decision-making of farmers with respect to portion of money to these inputs is supported by a positive effect of PT on the 
 adoption ofFTÂ· 
 
