 Social factors 
 
 Household decision-making with respect to the farming operation is influenced not only by the ecol).omic good qualities of actions but also by social factors 
 important to the household and those operating at community level. The influence of few of these factors on adoption of technologies is discussed below. 
 A large family often has a large number of working members. If this is the 
 case, then there will be more labour to exchange for an added ox or to 
 perform additional/helping farming operations such as furrow-making and other 
 manual (producing crops/helping something grow)s. The larger the family (X6 ), other things being constant, 
 the higher will be the chance of adoption of single-ox, bug-killers and (material that makes plants grow better) technologies. 
 As expected, family size has a positive effect on F T for both areas but a 
 mixed effect on adoption of PT and ST. The mixed effect may be because of 
 some unknown influences which were not (taken/took by force)/(taken/took control of) by (numbers that change/things that change) included in 
 the model. 
 In this part of Ethiopia, education (X 7 ) consists mainly of pre-school teaching through churches and the government reading and writing ability (series of actions to reach goals). In the same way/in that way, 
 education is expected to have a positive effect on adoption of all three production technologies. 
 The results show that education has a positive effect in most cases. However, 
 the level of importance is fairly low. This may, in part, be due to the large 
 number of (numbers that change/things that change), given a sample size of 100 or less and the (divided into two) 
 measurement ( 0, 1) of this (number or thing that changes) as argued/against other ways of measuring 
 education. 
 As with education, the index of exposure to outside information (X8 ) is found 
 to have a positive effect on the chance of adoption in most cases. However, 
 in he (related to studying numbers) sense this guess is supported in only two out of the six 
 cases tested. 
 If relatives (X 9 ) are seen as a source of added/more help in case of need, then 
 a farmer may try new practices. If they are seen as dependents, then he may 
 not be willing to adopt new technology. A previous study by Gunjal (1987) 
 found that in Seladengay the 'number of relatives' (used/put into action) a significant positive effect on the degree of risk disgust. In this study, the number of relatives 
 (X9 ) is found to have positive but non-significant effect in most cases. 
 Farming experience (X10 ), which is assumed to be monotonic with age, has 
 shown that, given the short rainy season, it is necessary to complete field operations on time. So, the more experience farmers have the less likely that 
 they will use a single-ox. On the other hand, the more experience a farmer has 
 in recognizing the importance of pests and the decline in life-creating ability status of his 
 farm lands, the higher is the chance of adopting PT and F TÂ· 
 The finding that experience (age) (uses/puts into action) a negative effect on adoption of 
 single-ox and (material that makes plants grow better) technologies and a positive effect on adoption of pes- 
 
 38 
 
 ticides is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the general (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) among the central highland 
 Ethiopian farmers. Bug-killers are seen as the only means (input) to control 
 pests, so even older farmers are willing to make use of them. The single-ox and 
 (material that makes plants grow better) represent, (match up each pair of items in order), changes in traditional cultural practices and 
 uncertain benefits because of rainfall (quality of changing over time or at different places). So, older farmers are less 
 likely to use these technologies. 
 Physical factors 
 
 Farming-based technologies are developed to help farmers overcome some of 
 the physical or technical restrictions to production. Two of these physical or 
 technical factors are carefully thought about/believed below. 
 The higher the value of the index of plot (features/ qualities/ traits), X 11 , the harder it is to work the soil with single-ox. It also makes any investment in 
 inputs such as (material that makes plants grow better) used on those plots less attractiv.e suggesting a negative 
 effect of X 11 on the adoption ofPT and FT. 
 The result show that X 11 has the expected negative effect on adoption of 
 ST, but the result is found (related to numbers) non -significant. This could be partly 
 due to measurement problems with respect to (taking by force)/(taking control of) the (quality of changing over time or at different places) of factors such as moisture content, physical and chemical properties of the soil, 
 exact slopes etc. The plot (features/ qualities/ traits) (number or thing that changes) was found highly related 
 with the adoption of bug-killer in the (material that makes plants grow better) model and coming together could 
 not be reached. Therefore, this (number or thing that changes) was dropped from the final model for 
 (material that makes plants grow better) adoption. 
 Traction power given by the Zebu breed is very low compared to the little bulls used in Asia (Reddy, 1982). In the same way/in that way, the need to secure survival/income 
 for the family might force decision makers to use more dependable sources of 
 traction power such as a pair of oxen instead of a single-ox. 
 As expected, the difficulty in traction power results in a negative and significant effect on adoption of ST in both areas. This hints that, given the 
 present state of animal traction technology, the use of a single-ox may not be 
 viewed by farmers as being very practical, ignoring the plot (features/ qualities/ traits). 
 Finally, combined testing of social, money-based and physical factors has shown that 
 money-based factors (use/put into action) (meaningful numbers) influence on divisible technologies (such as P T and F T) and that in areas where the family structure and the 
 degree of social ties among extended families is much stronger, social factors 
 (use/put into action) a big influence on adoption. 
 Risk and adoption of technologies 
 
 The purpose of this section is to see how the degree of risk disgust, R (X), 
 affects the adoption of the three production technologies. At first, the models 
 in equations (11), (12) and (13) were guessed. Some of the (related to how much money and power people have) 
 
 39 
 
 (numbers that change/things that change) that are not highly related to R (X) (i.e., relationship-related coefficient 
 less than 0.6) are later added to the final guessed equations. The results of 
 these models are presented in Table 3. 
 In general, the more risk disliking a farmer is, the less willing he is to change 
 the usual practices and try new technologies. The (understanding/ explanation) and the 
 influence of the different (related to how much money and power people have) factors on adoption of the three production technologies is the same as in the adoption models discussed earlier. 
 The chi -square values for testing the effects of all (numbers that change/things that change) except the (stopping or interfering with something) 
 on adoption are very different from zero for both areas. 
 In a separate study, most farmers in both study places/locations were found to be moderately to very risk disliking in relative terms ( Gunjal, 1987) suggesting that 
 they are less willing to adopt new inputs. TheÂ· results of this study point to/show 
 almost the same  effects for adoption of ST in both areas and for adoption of PT and F T 
