 (described the future) chances 
 The guessed models (shown in Table 2) were used to (describe the future) chances 
 of adoption of the three technologies at the mean level of explanatory (numbers that change/things that change). 
 As shown in Table 4, farmers in Ankober regularly show higher chance of adoption of all three production technologies than farmers in Seladengay. 
 The largest total difference in the chance of adoption happens with respect to adoption of the single-ox technology. This can be attributed mainly to 
 the fact that farmers in Seladengay show a greater habit/desire towards maintaining traditional cultural practices and have less outside contact to influence 
 their decision making than farmers in Ankober. On the other hand, test 
 of the influence of education on the chance of adoption, holding other factors at the mean level, shows a larger increase in the chance of adoption of 
 the three technologies in Seladengay than in Ankober. 4 This hints that improved education may really affect the adoption of new 
 technologies. 
 The percentages of farmers who were willing to use single-ox, bug-killer and 
 (material that makes plants grow better) for Ankober were (match up each pair of items in order) 54, 56 and 62%, while for Seladengay 
 the (pertaining to each person or thing) values were 33, 63 and 66%. From reviews of adoption studies 
 in developing countries (e.g., Feder et al., 1985) this rate of adoption seems 
 high. It is possible that these rates are over-guessed due to interest-free credit 
 and other perceived fringe benefits from the project. 62%, 
