 Ends/end results 
 The guessed models of adoption behaviour of farmers in Ethiopia point to/show 
 that money-based and technical (ability to be done) alone are not a (promise that something will definitely happen or that something will definitely work as described) for the adoption of technology. Social factors and the degree of risk disgust are equally 
 important. 
 The most significant money-based factor affecting adoption of single-ox, bug-killers and (material that makes plants grow better) technologies is farm size and the most significant social 
 factor is farming experience. The hit/effect of a change in farm size (i.e., (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) 
 reform) is likely to improves/increases production increasing technologies (bug-killers and (material that makes plants grow better)) but a negative effect on useful thing/valuable supply saving technology (single-ox). More exactly, a one percent change in farm size (at the 
 mean level of this and other (numbers that change/things that change)) is expected to change the chance of 
 adoption of ST, PT and F T by -9, + 1 and + 2 percent for Seladengay and by 
 -3, + 0.6 and + 1 percent for Ankober, (match up each pair of items in order). 
 It has also been shown that farming experience (uses/puts into action) a negative influence 
 on adoption of more risky technologies (e.g. single-ox and (material that makes plants grow better)) and a 
 positive influence on the adoption of less risky technology (e.g. bug-killers). 
 This is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the general (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) that most Ethiopian highland 
 farmers think about/believe bug-killer as the number one priority input. The high level of 
 importance of traction power also leads to a end/end result that improvement in 
 health and physical condition of oxen would make the single-ox technology 
 more practical and acceptable. (in almost the same way), other desirable changes in 
 plowing tools may also make this technology more acceptable to farmers. 
 The degree of risk disgust (uses/puts into action) a negative influence on the adoption of 
 production technologies in most cases. Given that adoption of technologies is 
 a necessary step towards increasing food production, it is very important to reduce 
 the level of risk disgust through better education, outside contact and other 
 appropriate measures. The results show that the hit/effect of education on the 
 chance of adoption of each of the three technologies is big. 
 So, policies designed to improve the money-based, social and physical factors 
 affecting farming systems, almost the same as  Ankober and Seladengay areas, are likely 
 to help increase the participation of farmers in development projects involving 
 new farming-based technologies and increase food production in Ethiopia. 
